## 📘 Must-Read Lecture Notes (Free Online)
- **CMU Lecture Notes on Introduction to Cryptography** (Vipul Goyal, 2020)  
  Covers classical ciphers, one-time pad, Shannon’s theorem, one-way functions, pseudorandomness, and group theory. Excellent for optimization researchers since it emphasizes computational hardness assumptions.   [CMU School of Computer Science](https://www.cs.cmu.edu/~goyal/15356/lecture_notes.pdf)  

- **A Course in Theory of Cryptography** (Sanjam Garg, UC Berkeley, 2026 draft)  
  Comprehensive notes: one-way functions, pseudorandomness, private/public key cryptography, digital signatures, secure computation, and obfuscation. Good for bridging into advanced topics like homomorphic encryption.   [crypto-berkeley.github.io](https://crypto-berkeley.github.io/cs276-spring26/assets/lecture-notes/notes.pdf)  

- **MIT OpenCourseWare – Selected Topics in Cryptography** (Prof. Ran Canetti, 2004)  
  Graduate-level notes on multiparty computation, zero-knowledge proofs, and universal composability. Useful once you want to understand secure optimization protocols.   [MIT OpenCourseWare](https://ocw.mit.edu/courses/6-897-selected-topics-in-cryptography-spring-2004/pages/lecture-notes/)  

- **Columbia University – Introduction to Cryptography** (Lecture summaries, 2025)  
  Accessible notes with examples of perfect secrecy, one-time pad, pseudorandom generators, and computational security definitions.   [Department of Computer Science, Columbia University](https://www.cs.columbia.edu/~tal/4261/F25/lectures.html)  

